ds to more fibrous and cartilage tissue, which connects bone fragments and reduces strain, allowing blood vessels to invade and replace the cartilage with bone over 8-16 weeks.","target":"More interfragmentary movement in a fracture leads to more fibrous and cartilage tissue, which connects bone fragments and reduces strain, allowing blood vessels to invade and replace the cartilage with bone over 8-16 weeks.","line":9},{"title":"The direction of interfragmentary movement (IFM) is critical for fracture healing; axial movements aid in mending, while shear movements hinder vascularization and bone formation due to distortional strain.","target":"The direction of interfragmentary movement (IFM) is critical for fracture healing; axial movements aid in mending, while shear movements hinder vascularization and bone formation due to distortional strain.","line":9},{"title":"@Wildemann_2021_202406171535","target":"@Wildemann_2021_202406171535","line":16}],"key":"000 Zettelkasten/Interfragmentary movement (IFM) is the axial compression, tension, and shear movements in the callus area..md"},
